body:
Hello,

When using the `--x-assign unique` flag, it seams concatenation of don't care values and other values behaves happily until a 64-bit width, but triggers an internal error for wider values. Here is a 65-bit example.

`BasicRTL.v`:
```verilog
module BasicRTL (input wire clock, input wire reset);
  wire [64:0] v;
  assign v = {8'bxxxxxxxx, 57'h2a};
  always @(posedge clock) begin
    $write ("test: ", "%d", v, "\n");
  end
endmodule
```

`BasicRTL.cpp`:
```cpp
#include <verilated.h>
#include "VBasicRTL.h"
VBasicRTL *top;
vluint64_t main_time = 0;
double sc_time_stamp () {
  return main_time;
}
int main(int argc, char** argv) {
  Verilated::commandArgs(argc, argv);
  top = new VBasicRTL;
  while (!Verilated::gotFinish()) {
    top->clock = 0; top->eval();
    top->clock = 1; top->eval();
    main_time++;
  }
  top->final(); delete top; return 0;
}
```

Build output:

```
$ verilator -cc BasicRTL.v -exe BasicRTL.cpp -o BasicRTL --x-assign unique
perl: warning: Setting locale failed.
perl: warning: Please check that your locale settings:
	LANGUAGE = "en_GB:en",
	LC_ALL = (unset),
	LANG = "en_GB.UTF-8"
    are supported and installed on your system.
perl: warning: Falling back to the standard locale ("C").
%Error: Internal Error: BasicRTL.v:3:14: ../V3EmitC.cpp:2059: Wide Op w/ no temp, perhaps missing op in V3EmitC?
    3 |   assign v = {8'bxxxxxxxx, 57'h2a};
      |              ^
                        ... See the manual at https://verilator.org/verilator_doc.html for more assistance.
```

**Edit**: this was observed with `Verilator 4.202 2021-04-24 rev v4.200-110-g15f7741ea` as well as with `Verilator 4.211 devel rev v4.210-74-g34a0bb44`, but _not_ with `Verilator 4.028 2020-02-06 rev v4.026-92-g890cecc1`.

**Edit 2**: doesn't look like quite the same thing, but could possibly be related to #3040?

I believe this should be expected to "just work" like it does for narrower values.
(I couldn't find whether this problem should be reported as a bug or not, I hope someone can tag the issue appropriately.)

Thanks for reading through that one!
